🌐 Computer Networks
1️⃣ DNS (Domain Name System)
Simple Idea

DNS converts human-friendly names → IP addresses

Example:

google.com → 142.250.x.x
Mental Model (Phone Contacts 📱)

You don’t remember numbers, you save names.

Name → “Mom”

Actual number → 98765xxxx

DNS works exactly like this.

How It Works (Step-by-Step)

You type google.com

DNS server finds its IP

Browser connects using IP

Website loads

Why It Works

Because humans cannot remember IP addresses.

Connection to Programming

Think of it like:

map["google.com"] = "142.250.x.x"
Memory Trick 🧠

DNS = Internet Phonebook

2️⃣ ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)
Simple Idea

ARP converts:

👉 IP address → MAC address

Mental Model (Finding a House 🏠)

You know:

City address (IP)

But delivery needs:

Exact house (MAC)

ARP helps find the exact device inside network.

How It Works

Device broadcasts:
“Who has this IP?”

Target device replies:
“I have it, here is my MAC”

Why It Works

Inside LAN, communication happens using MAC address, not IP.

Memory Trick

DNS: Name → IP
ARP: IP → MAC

3️⃣ HTTP vs HTTPS
HTTP (HyperText Transfer Protocol)

Used for web communication

Not secure

Data sent in plain text

HTTPS (Secure HTTP)

Encrypted communication

Uses SSL/TLS

Safe for passwords, banking

Mental Model

📨 HTTP = Open postcard
🔒 HTTPS = Sealed envelope

Why It Works

Encryption ensures:

privacy

data integrity

security

Real Example

When you see 🔒 in browser → HTTPS

Memory Trick

HTTPS = HTTP + Security

4️⃣ Routing (How Data Finds Path)
Simple Idea

Routing decides which path data should take.

Mental Model (Google Maps 🗺️)

You want to go from:

Bangalore → Delhi

Maps choose best route based on:

traffic

distance

Routers do the same for data.

How It Works

Routers maintain routing tables

Choose best path for packets

Why It Works

Internet is huge → multiple paths exist → routing selects best one.

Connection to DSA

Similar to:

Shortest path algorithms (Dijkstra)

Memory Trick

Routing = Path finding for data

